    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "No, it should be `>`. We want it to no-op if someone tries to exit or activate twice in an epoch.\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n* Validator A (not previously exited) submits an `Exit`. It is included near the start of the epoch.\r\n* Validator A's `exit_epoch` is set to `entry_exit_epoch(current_epoch)`\r\n* Validator A submits another exit in the same epoch. It is attempted to be included in the block.\r\n* Two possibilities:\r\n    * If the condition is: \"Verify that validator.exit_epoch > get_entry_exit_effect_epoch(get_current_epoch(state))\", then we see that the exit_epoch is not greater than the entry exit epoch of the current epoch and it is a no-op.\r\n    * If the condition is: \"Verify that validator.exit_epoch >= get_entry_exit_effect_epoch(get_current_epoch(state))\", then we see that the exit_epoch is greater than or equal (equal in this case) and this condition does not guard against the op.",
